This guide explains how to give AI coding agents current Trellis instructions
when they work in an out-of-tree service repository.

Use the raw files as stable, pasteable references:

- Short guide: <https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/llms.txt>
- Full guide: <https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/llms-full.txt>
- AGENTS template: `/templates/trellis-service-AGENTS.md`

## When to use each file

Use `llms.txt` as a small bootstrap document for every Trellis task. It tells an
agent to use deployment authority and identity authority wording, prefer generated surfaces,
and avoid stale service APIs.

Use `llms-full.txt` when the agent will change a contract, generated SDK usage,
service handlers, operations, event publication, or outbox/inbox code. It includes
examples for TypeScript and Rust services.

Copy `templates/trellis-service-AGENTS.md` into an out-of-tree service repository
as `AGENTS.md`, then fill in the local commands and paths. Keep local rules in
that file; keep Trellis-wide rules linked to the raw guides.

## Recommended setup for a service repo

1. Copy the template:

   ```sh
   curl -fsSL \
     https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/templates/trellis-service-AGENTS.md \
     -o AGENTS.md
   ```

2. Fill in the repository-specific contract path, generation command, format
   command, typecheck command, test command, run command, and migration command.
3. Link the raw `llms.txt` and `llms-full.txt` URLs from any other AI-facing
   project instructions.
4. Ask agents to read the short guide for all Trellis tasks and the full guide for
   contract or runtime-surface changes.

## TypeScript instructions for agents

Use generated, surface-first APIs:

```ts
const order = await client.rpc.orders.get({ orderId: "ord_123" }).orThrow();

await client.event.orders.shipped.publish({
  orderId: "ord_123",
  customerId: "cust_456",
  shippedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
}).orThrow();

const feed = await client.feed.orders.live({ customerId: "cust_456" }).orThrow();

const op = await client.operation.orders.process
  .start({ orderId: "ord_123" })
  .orThrow();
```

Register service providers through `service.handle`. Handler code should use the
scoped `client` argument for allowed outbound calls:

```ts
import { Result } from "@qlever-llc/trellis";

await service.handle.rpc.orders.get(async ({ input, client }) => {
  const order = await loadOrder(input.orderId);
  if (!order) return Result.err(orderNotFound(input.orderId));

  await client.event.orders.viewed.publish({
    orderId: input.orderId,
    viewedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  }).orThrow();

  return Result.ok(order);
});
```

For events, direct publish is the default. Use `prepare(...)` and an outbox only
when event enqueue must commit with service-local durable state:

```ts
import {
  OutboxDispatcher,
  SqlOutboxRepository,
  type SqlExecutor,
} from "@qlever-llc/trellis/service";

const outboxRepository = new SqlOutboxRepository(dbExecutor, "postgres");
// `outboundClient` is the publisher used by the dispatch worker.
const outboxDispatcher = new OutboxDispatcher(outboxRepository, outboundClient, {
  idleRetryMs: 30_000,
});

const prepared = client.event.orders.shipped.prepare({
  orderId: input.orderId,
  customerId: input.customerId,
  shippedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
}).orThrow();

await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  await markOrderShipped(tx, input.orderId);

  const executor: SqlExecutor = drizzleTransactionExecutor(tx);
  const outbox = new SqlOutboxRepository(executor, "postgres");
  await outbox.enqueue(prepared);
});

outboxDispatcher.notify(); // after commit; debounced and single-flight
```

Do not signal from inside the transaction. Notify only after commit so the
dispatcher cannot publish work that later rolls back.

Use `SqlInboxRepository` only for handlers that are not naturally idempotent. Use
`NatsKvOutboxRepository` and `NatsKvInboxRepository` only when NATS KV durability
is sufficient and no unrelated database transaction must be atomic.

For durable service event processing, require an explicit `eventConsumers` group
in the service contract and register the listener during service startup with
that group:

```ts
await service.event.orders.shipped.listen(handleShipment, {}, {
  group: "shipmentProjection",
}).orThrow();
```

Never invent `durableName` values in service code. Trellis provisions the
physical consumer and grants only that bound consumer to the service token.
Handler-injected clients may publish and prepare events, but they must not
register listeners.

## Rust instructions for agents

Use generated descriptors and facades. Prefer generated wrappers when available:

```rust
let response = orders_client
    .rpc()
    .orders()
    .get(&orders_sdk::OrdersGetRequest {
        order_id: "ord_123".into(),
    })
    .await?;
```

Use descriptor APIs for events and operations:

```rust
trellis_client
    .publish::<orders_sdk::events::OrdersShippedEventDescriptor>(
        &orders_sdk::OrdersShippedEvent {
            order_id: "ord_123".into(),
            customer_id: "cust_456".into(),
            shipped_at: now_iso(),
        },
    )
    .await?;

let mut events = trellis_client
    .subscribe::<orders_sdk::events::OrdersShippedEventDescriptor>()
    .await?;

let op = trellis_client
    .operation::<orders_sdk::operations::OrdersProcessOperation>()
    .start(&orders_sdk::OrdersProcessInput {
        order_id: "ord_123".into(),
    })
    .await?;
```

Register service providers through generated handler facades when available:

```rust
service.handle().rpc().orders().get(get_order_handler);
service.handle().feed().orders().live(orders_live_stream);
service.handle().operation().orders().process(orders_process_provider);
```

Use `prepare_event::<Descriptor>(...)` and an outbox only when event enqueue must
commit with local durable state:

```rust
use trellis_rs::client::{dispatch_outbox_once, OutboxStore, SqliteOutboxStore};

let prepared = trellis_client.prepare_event::<
    orders_sdk::events::OrdersShippedEventDescriptor,
>(&orders_sdk::OrdersShippedEvent {
    order_id: "ord_123".into(),
    customer_id: "cust_456".into(),
    shipped_at: now_iso(),
})?;

let tx = sqlite.transaction()?;
mark_order_shipped(&tx, "ord_123")?;

{
    let mut outbox = SqliteOutboxStore::new(&tx);
    outbox.enqueue("outbox:ord_123:shipped", &prepared).await?;
}

tx.commit()?;

let mut outbox = SqliteOutboxStore::new(&sqlite);
dispatch_outbox_once(&mut outbox, |event| async {
    trellis_client.publish_prepared(&event).await
})
.await?;
```

Use `SqliteInboxStore` or `PostgresInboxStore` only for non-idempotent handlers.
Use `PostgresOutboxStore` for Postgres-backed outboxes. Use `NatsKvOutboxStore`
and `NatsKvInboxStore` only when NATS KV durability is sufficient and no unrelated
database transaction must be atomic.

## What to ask agents to verify

Ask agents to run the service repo's own commands. Common checks are:

```sh
deno fmt
deno check **/*.ts
deno test

npm run format
npm run typecheck
npm test

cargo fmt
cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings
cargo test --all-features
```

If contracts changed, also run the repository's Trellis generation command and
verify generated artifacts are updated from the source contract.
